english:
  title: Preface to Poems Sent to Minister Lin Upon His Departure as Inspector of Punghae Province
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The art of verse and song most often flows from the farewells of friends. In ancient times, when Shen Bo received his fief at Xie and Zhong Shanfu journeyed to Qi, Yin Jifu composed songs to send them off. The praise, encouragement, and exhortation in those verses shine brilliantly among the three hundred poems of the Classic, becoming the model for all who would make poetry in later ages.

    Now Minister Lin of Pyeongdaek departs as Inspector of Punghae Province, and Minister Ha of Hao Pavilion has composed the first verse of farewell, capturing the very spirit that Yin Jifu once embodied. Our Minister Lin possesses both the benevolent heart that soothes the people and the nimble wit to adapt to all circumstances. In his early years, he served as magistrate of Uiju, where the people so trusted his integrity and justice that none dared deceive him. When reports came of border disturbances, he judged with righteousness and prevented recklessness. After two years, his reputation flourished greatly, and by his merit he was promoted to Director of the Ministry of Works. While serving there, when a commander of veteran rank was appointed garrison commandant, the Dowager King, knowing Minister Lin's worth, made him chief of staff with authority to act as circumstances demanded, free from the commander's directives. Thus entrusted completely, both ruler and commander treated him generously, delegating all military affairs to his care. In the intervals of his duties, he would spread open the poetry collection of Master Zhu before him and spend the day in recitation and contemplation—yet not a single matter went unaccomplished.

    In the year Byungja, he was appointed Vice Minister of the State Council and concurrent Commander of Niseong Province. Soon after, he was transferred as Inspector-General of the Northwest Region, and within a year, changed to Inspector of Gyeongsang Province. Wherever his authority reached, officials trembled with vigilance. When famine struck and the southern people faced starvation, he devised every measure to provide relief, ensuring not one soul perished by the roadside. Upon the present king's accession, moved by his loyalty and virtue, he was again appointed Vice Minister of the State Council, and shortly thereafter sent forth as Governor of Seoul. His reputation for employing the capable and gaining public esteem has only grown with time—surely worthy of Minister Ha's praise and encouragement.

    The upper verse of his poem echoes those lines from the "Steaming People" speaking of "noble bearing and noble countenance, careful and reverent, reverent and careful." The lower verse recalls the "Lofty Peak" which says "may you establish this southern realm, and generation after generation maintain its achievements." Many other lines similarly reflect such classical echoes. This is natural for Minister Ha, and the works of both Duke Dogok and Duke Eoheun show the same quality. I believe their intention was not merely to imitate the ancients, but rather that when words flow as verse and speech becomes song, hearts aligned and spirits matched, they naturally embody what came before without seeking to do so.

    Being both kin and long companion to Minister Lin, I went ahead to wait for him at Yellow Bridge Stream. When he arrived as dusk fell, he drew forth this scroll and entrusted it to me, asking that I compose these opening words to grace its beginning.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Shen Bo and Zhong Shanfu were historical figures from classical Chinese antiquity whose departures were commemorated in the Book of Poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: Yin Jifu was a sage whose poems in the Book of Poetry became exemplars of farewell verses for later generations.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'three hundred poems' alludes to the traditional count of poems in the Classic of Poetry (Shijing).
  - key: ''
    value: Minister Ha of Hao Pavilion is the poet who wrote the farewell verses mentioned in this preface.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhu Xi (Master Zhu/Zhu Wenggong) was the great Neo-Confucian philosopher whose collected works were studied throughout East Asia.
  - key: ''
    value: The poems referenced—'Steaming People' (烝民) and 'Lofty Peak' (崧高)—are specific odes from the Classic of Poetry known for their celebration of virtue and enduring merit.
